nvidia's recent impact on the quantum computing stock trade can be attributed to comments made by its ceo, jensen huang, about the timeline for practical quantum computing. here's how it unfolded: comments by nvidia ceo: during an investor meeting, jensen huang stated that "very useful" quantum computers are likely decades away. he suggested a timeline of 15 to 30 years for quantum computing to reach a stage where it would be widely applicable, which is significantly longer than what many investors might have been anticipating. this led to a reassessment of the immediate market potential for quantum computing technologies. market reaction: following these remarks, stocks of several quantum computing companies, including ionq inc., rigetti computing, d-wave quantum, and quantum computing inc., experienced significant drops in after-hours trading. the stocks fell between 3% and 15% immediately after huang's comments, with some losing up to 25% in pre-market trading the next day. this reaction reflects investor skepticism about the near-term profitability or practical application of quantum computing technologies. nvidia's position: nvidia itself is not developing a quantum computer but has been positioning itself as a key player in the quantum computing ecosystem through software and hybrid solutions. nvidia's cuda quantum platform, for instance, allows developers to simulate quantum algorithms on gpus before deploying them on actual quantum processors. huang's comments could be seen as a strategic move to manage expectations, focusing on nvidia's role in the interim classical-quantum hybrid computing phase, where nvidia's technology would continue to be relevant. industry outlook: huang's prediction has cast a shadow over the quantum computing industry, which has been seen as a speculative and high-growth area. his comments suggest that while quantum computing holds significant promise, its commercial viability might still be a long way off, impacting investor sentiment towards individual quantum computing companies. this has led to a broader reevaluation of investment in quantum computing stocks. in summary, nvidia's ceo's remarks about the distant future of practical quantum computing applications led to a significant sell-off in quantum computing stocks, reflecting a recalibration of investor expectations in this emerging field.

there are understandably a lot of "defai" (aifi?) skeptics, but i do think there are merits to simplifying defi interactions through ai agents. we all agree that defi is amazing - you can trustlessly borrow money, earn yield, and trade assets without needing to go through a middleman. however, interfacing with defi applications right now is often too complex or confusing for the average user (even crypto natives!). it's very unlikely that retail users will buy eth from a cex, move their eth onchain, deposit it into lido, and take the resulting steth and deposit that into aave/balancer/yearn/etc to earn bonus yield. imagine a world where you can tell an ai agent "find a way to earn 8% yield on my eth with minimal risk" and it goes an executes everything autonomously behind the scenes. that's much simpler for the user, and they won't have to go through the staking/deposit/transfer process manually. i think this could be a big unlock for defi teams looking to find more reach outside of the current crypto space. obviously a lot more advancements would need to be made on the agent side, but this could make defi accessible to a new cohort of users.

crackdown on ai chip exports, us lashes out at china: here are the global impacts - report key points - the u.s. department of commerce and other regulatory agencies released regulations at a frenetic pace as the biden administration wrapped up its term this month, as the new "export control framework for artificial intelligence (ai) diffusion". - the framework for the diffusion of artificial intelligencewas published on january 15, 2025. bis has implemented significant additional controls on advanced computing chips and certain closed ai model weights, as well as new licensing exceptions and updates to validated end-user (veu) permissions. the framework adopts a â€œthree-pronged strategyâ€ that i) requires authorizations for exports, re-exports and transfers of advanced node ics to a broad range of countries; (ii) establishes new controls on the weights of more advanced ai models, including a new fdp rule that applies such controls to certain weights of models produced abroad using advanced computer chips made with u.s. technology or equipment; and iii) imposes additional security conditions relating to the preservation of certain ai models. while the rule is effective immediately, the expected compliance date for these rules is set for may 15, 2025, with some elements of these controls having a delayed compliance date of january 15, 2026. - biden's restrictions on the export of ai chips aim to prevent the technology from being misused. however, large companies fear high costs and market loss, while excluded countries express concern about limited access to advanced technologies. - these new regulations appear primarily aimed at limiting china's ability to further develop certain critical technologies, such as artificial intelligence (ai), or access the us market, but each has a broader impact and could have some unintended consequences for industries hit. - it remains to be seen whether and how the implementation of these rules will be reviewed in the coming months, particularly in light of president trump's "day one" executive orders (eos) implementing a regulatory freeze and reversing many actions taken by the biden administration. - to the extent that these rules impose restrictions on china, an area where the two administrations have historically been largely aligned, they are more likely to be maintained under the new administration. other rules can be canceled or changed. - we expect to issue more in-depth notices as we learn more about the new administration's plans for these rules. in the meantime, we recommend that companies consider the potential impact of the rules and be prepared to implement any necessary changes. extremaratio china usa liminalwarfare chip artificialintellgence read our latest reportat

does the president of columbia not have access to ai? if the united states put a 50% import tariff on colombia and columbia retaliated with a 50% import tariff on the usa, which economy would suffer most and what would be the likely final outcome? the impact of a reciprocal 50% import tariff between the united states and colombia would likely be more severe on colombia's economy for several reasons: 1. *economic size and diversification*: - the u.s. has a much larger and more diversified economy compared to colombia. the u.s. can more easily shift its trade to other countries or increase domestic production for goods that were previously imported from colombia. colombia, on the other hand, might find it harder to find alternative markets for its exports due to its smaller economic scale and less diversified export base. 2. *trade dependence*: - colombia might be more dependent on exports to the u.s. for key sectors like coffee, flowers, coal, and oil. a significant portion of colombia's gdp is tied to these exports. conversely, the u.s. has a broad range of trade partners, and the percentage of its trade with colombia is relatively small. 3. *consumer and industry impact*: - u.s. consumers might face higher prices for colombian goods like coffee, but these are not critical in terms of volume or necessity. in contrast, colombian industries and consumers might suffer more from higher costs of u.s. imports, which could include technology, machinery, and consumer goods that are significant for economic or daily life. *likely final outcome:* - *negotiation and trade agreement*: both countries would likely engage in negotiations to reduce or eliminate the tariffs. the u.s. might leverage its larger market and economic influence to push for a resolution that favors its interests, possibly leading to new trade agreements or adjustments in existing ones. - *economic pressure*: colombia might experience more economic pressure, potentially leading to domestic economic challenges like inflation, job losses in export sectors, and reduced economic growth. this pressure could expedite negotiations from the colombian side. - *third-party influence*: other countries or international bodies like the wto might mediate or influence outcomes, encouraging a return to more open trade policies to prevent wider economic disruptions. - *long-term economic adjustments*: both countries might seek to diversify their trade partners further, with colombia possibly looking to strengthen ties with other latin american countries or asia. the u.s. might accelerate policies aimed at increasing domestic production or sourcing from different regions. the exact outcome would depend on numerous variables including political will, global economic conditions, and the strategic importance each country places on their bilateral relationship. however, given the relative economic strengths, colombia would likely feel the pinch more acutely, pushing for a quicker resolution.

the decline in imports due to sanctions has a disproportionately strong impact on russian industry. a 1% reduction in supply costs leads to a 2â€“3.1% drop in output in manufacturing industries within a year. high-tech sectors, such as automotive and mechanical engineering, are particularly vulnerable, as their dependence on imported components is most pronounced. in 2022, the effect of sanctions was especially noticeable: each 1 percentage point decrease in intermediate imports resulted in a 1.14% drop in output in the current quarter and a 1.33% decline in the following one. non-resource exports, particularly machinery and equipment, also suffered, contracting by 16% over the two quarters following an import shock. to compensate for the losses, russia redirected supplies through neutral countries such as armenia and kazakhstan, but this led to higher logistics costs and more complex payment processes. in the long term, sanctions continue to have a negative impact on output and exports, as adapting to the new conditions requires significant resources and time.

the dilemma in lping uniswap v2 vs. v3 imo, the dilemma of univ2 and univ3 hightlights the trade-offs between inventory risks (for makers) and trading experience (for takers). v2: univ2 benefits makers (lpers) by offering a straightforward, passive liquidity provision model with uniform liquidity distribution across the entire pricing curve. this simplicity reduces the complexity of managing position and minimizes the il for lpers. however, from the perspective of takers, the average trading price (measured by price slippage) is the only thing takers care. univ2 suffers from low capital efficiency, leading to higher slippage for takers. v3: in the opposite side, univ3 introduces concentrated liquidity, allowing lpers to deploy funds within specific price ranges, significantly improving capital efficiency and reducing slippage for takers. while it benefits takers with better pricing, it places a heavier burden on makers, who now face high il risks and must actively monitor their positions to avoid permanent losses. that creates a dilemma: univ2 prioritizes ease and security for makers, while univ3 optimizes for takers' trading experience at the cost of increased complexity and il risks for makers. as a lper, which model you prefer, univ2 or v3? please comment below

this paper explores trade-offs in solving compositional reasoning questions (crqs) using different architectures. the paper proposes deep transformers, rnns, and chain of thought (cot) transformers as solutions, each with resource trade-offs. deep transformers exploit parallelism but need depth scaling with question complexity. rnns offer constant depth, trading parameter size and sequential processing for efficiency. chain of thought achieves constant size models, but at the cost of increased runtime and less parallelism. - methods explored in this paper : â†’ deep transformers solve crqs with depth proportional to problem depth. â†’ rnns achieve constant depth solutions with logarithmic hidden dimension, but require specific input order. â†’ cot transformers use constant depth but generate tokens linearly proportional to problem size. â†’ the paper provides constructions and proves necessity for depth in transformers and hidden dimension/token count in rnns/cot respectively. - paper - arxiv. org/abs/2503.01544v1 paper title: "compositional reasoning with transformers, rnns, and chain of thought"

okay let's see if i can clarify my position in a tweet. here goes nothing. trump tariffs? good? bad? crazy? let's set some context: america has a debt problem. this is our greatest single threat. not china. not ai. not pandemic. so what happens when you end up with runaway sovereign debt? eventually, you gotta pay the piper. there was never any plan, just politicians preserving their career and kicking the can down the road, making it someone else's problem. and voters keep voting for short term interests. "keep my prices low right now! keep my jobs good right now!" short term thinking is one of the greatest weaknesses of democracy. so now you have elon and doge trying to get control of thisâ€”time will tell if this plays out like they think it will. fdr tried radical interventions during the great depression and they had moderate impacts, but the depression didn't really end until the wartime economy of wwii kicked in. interpretations vary greatly. my personal take; massive wartime spending, and the technological boom after, were the primary reasons for the depression to end. well, no one wants another world war, so how do you get off this game of debt chicken? geopolitical theory for the last few decades has been the breton woods modelâ€”globalism, bilateral trade, and economic interdependence (combined with democratizing missions) were the best way to prosperity and preventing war. well, globalism has been declared a failure. economic enmeshment didn't stop russia from invading ukraine, iran from seeking nukes, or china from arming up. so, what's left to us? aside from an expensive hot war that no one wants, what's the path to prosperity and peace? austerity measurements and free market theory are certainly part of it. just look at argentinian turnaround under javier milei. short term pain, long term gain is the theory. get the government out of the way and let the market innovate out of it. but american economy is based on trade and innovation far more than argentina. furthermore, we have reserve currency status, and economic warfare is one of our primary geopolitical tools. economic sanctions can slow down our adversaries, but not stop them (russia, iran, china, etc, they always find a way). combine all this with the brewing cold war with china, and you've got caught between a rock and a hard place. we've got sovereign debt on one side and geopolitical tension on the other. so now you have multiple threats, within and without. the pandemic and other events, like the suez canal blockage in 2021, showed just how fragile our long supply chains are. long supply chains are a huge vulnerability. so now a long term strategy starts to form. you dramatically cut government spending voluntarily before you're forced to do so from a catastrophic debt crunch. then, you on-shore your entire economy (if you can) because resources inside your own borders is the only thing you can sure of if the rest of the world comes unglued. just look at how access to chips turned out to be crippling to russia, to the point they were scavenging electronics from dishwashers. so yeah, does it look stupid when trump complains about trade deficits? yeah, but all his advisors have read the same books i have. trade deficits are a superficial excuse. the real game is a long game. we're trying to avoid going off a debt cliff, which to be clear, would be far more painful than what we're going through now. we're also trying to shore up defenses before war breaks out. ideally, if we succeed at both, we can avoid a second great depression as well as avoid world war 3. so do i agree with the tariffs? in principle, yeah. in the long run. could it have been done better? possibly. but i get the sense that trump wants to get stuff done quickly. he's old, he's probably not getting a third term, and he's out of fucks to give. is it painful now? absolutely. will it get worse before it gets better? almost certainly. is it better than the alternative? also yes. will it work? remains to be seen. honestly, it seems like doge isn't aggressive enough and just the tariffs might not be enough. the reason we're here is from kicking the can down the road for too long. if you really want to blame anyone, look in the mirror. voters didn't take this seriously. now the jig is up. sources: 1. new world order - ray dalio 2. great power politics - john mearsheimer 3. why nations fail - acemoglu and robinson 4. basic economics - thomas sowell 5. vulture capitalism - grace blakely 6. capital - thomas piketty

we keep calling it a trade war, but are we underestimating the war part? too often, economic conflict gets framed through spreadsheets and supply chains. but make no mistake: what we're watching unfold is a multi-domain, long-duration struggle over power, resilience, and technological dominance. this isn't just about tariffs. this is about controlling the architecture of the future economy. what does the battlespace look like? theaters: taiwan strait, red sea, cyberspace, undersea cables instruments: semiconductor embargoes, outbound investment screening, data sovereignty laws, energy corridor security maneuvers: reshoring, friendshoring, aukus, bri, digital currency experiments victory is different depending on where you stand for the u.s., it's about securing critical supply chains, maintaining semiconductor leadership, and reinforcing a rules-based order. for china, it's about achieving technological self-sufficiency and rewriting the global economic rulebook on its own terms. casualties? the global south, pulled between superpowers. multinationals caught in compliance limbo. consumers, facing inflation from fractured logistics. economists, still applying old trade models to a new kind of conflict. this isn't just a debate about gdp or trade balances. it's clausewitz meets coase, playing out in boardrooms, ports, and code. are we ready for what this means?

britain's free trade platform economy worked the same way microsoft's did/does. salt the earth around your moat, force everyone to work on your platform, then capture much of the massive surplus value that's created within your empire. if america's high value tech companies are at the top of the value chain, like britain's domestic manufacturing of old, then the obvious desire of a hypothetical american empire would be for its highest value industries to transact with zero barriers across the whole of the empire. and so. zuckerberg learned mandarin. went to china. pleaded his case, even after a state-sponsored hack of google servers targeting political dissidents forced google to withdraw from china. more! he asked xi jinping to name his firstborn. zoomers will say i'm lying! surely not! he got a gold chain and a delenda est shirt?! but it did. and yet. he was snubbed. america's tech companies were shut out of the world's fastest growing market. uber was invited in and then raided for parts. baidu learned that early internet users were trying to pirate media. so they built an interface to make it even easier! i imagine our high value media producing industries were unhappy about this. alas, there was no recourse. europe's in a similar boat. only allowed to sell products if they donate all their ip. bmw is forced to invest billions of euros in the desiccated husk of a corporate shell, "brilliance auto", appropriated by the ccp from its founder who now lives in exile in america. brilliant. the relationship is much worse than it otherwise could be for america. if we have only a "high value" economy at home, while our primary geopolitical-economic rival maintains the full stack of high-med-low value industries in a vertically integrated domestic platform economy. sure, we can focus on "building new branches" - and then be unable to sell those branches to our richest trading partner. "yeah man, you just focus on building slack. it'll work out for you, i promise," says the microsoft exec to the slack exec. or to the dropbox exec. oops. this is not an argument against the currency problem or an argument in favor of blasting random tariffs. you still have to solve the former and only use the latter with tact. but it is an argument against the idea that america should shy away from neomercantilism. we could pretend to be "free" from it in a unipolar world, when the people playing it thrived under our umbrella - because then, sure, there were negative impacts on domestic industry, but at least our high value goods were able to dominate their markets. we benefited massively still. "what is seen and what is not seen," nods bastiat from the grave. alas, what is not seen includes the future growth potential of any given industry - and the current economic & geopolitical status of france today vs. in the 1800s. > "the only places where america is competitive and profitable is the things only it can make: software, social networks, advanced ai, cars that drive themselves" the reason no other nation on earth has built a meaningfully valuable tech sector is that they have to compete with america. they get crushed. china didn't let america compete and now has a functional tech sector that serves its (increasingly valuable) domestic market. this is a damn shame if you're an american equities holder! imagine what the "mag 7" could've been worth during the last bubble if china's tech sector was as developed as europe's. if we had to export all the industry and jobs for people who score <1400 on the sat, maybe it could've worked out long term if the whole world ran on our operating system. i'm skeptical, but maybe. the s&p500 would be over $10k already, at least. but of course it's not going to work if we don't get to have the cake or eat it too. of course the people who end up on the losing end of the trade will throw a fit. and fair play to them for doing so. i don't know that "what is a country for?" is the right question. but certainly "who is a country for?" is a reasonable one for a body politic to ask. a nation whose elite collectively answer: "not you" is going to be a volatile place. and that will ultimately lead to a very "anti abundance" outcome. if you like building great things and civilizational progress, keeping the domestic population happy and wealthy and productive and engaged with you in that act of building is a tier 1 imperative! "just tax all the productive assets/people into oblivion" is the inevitable call of one half the demos if you let this play out too far. "just exclude all of my outgroup from the market" is the inevitable call of the other half. sometimes both halves will even agree on bizarro regulatory-protectionism, like gdpr or other such nonsense. no matter what, it's bad for people who like building things. any given set of policies being pursued at the current moment is already an output of this process having gone way, way wrong - and therefore is guaranteed to be horrifically bad in all sorts of ways. but that doesn't mean a defense of the status quo makes sense either. the status quo necessitates either this reaction, or one in the opposite direction. you can't go back to it any more than the knuckleheads can go back to 1950. neomercantilism is worth the earnest consideration of smart western elites because it offers a path to involve the demos in production, in advancing the frontier, in building something great, and ultimately in economic activity with enormous tams and the ability to absorb huge amounts of capital & labor productively. might it trade some t=0 aggregate welfare away? undoubtedly. but the people are going to do that anyway. they already have a thousand times over - that's leviathan and it's choking productivity all around us at the city, state, and federal levels. might as well make the trade one that has a chance of having a positive return on investment at t+5.

revive and secure its semiconductor industry, while laying the foundation for a structured digital transformation. in a world defined by geopolitical tensions, technological shortages, and rapid digitalization, japan is seeking to reclaim its role in the global high-tech ecosystem. semiconductors are recognized as a cornerstone of japanâ€™s digital infrastructure. they power key technologies such as 5g, ai, iot, autonomous vehicles, robotics, smart cities, and cybersecurity. as such, they are not merely industrial products, but strategic assets essential to national security. to realize this vision, the japanese government has developed a roadmap built on three complementary pillars: strengthening domestic production, developing next-generation technologies, and building a sustainable human and industrial ecosystem. a key initiative in this plan is the establishment of japan advanced semiconductor manufacturing (jasm), a symbol of japanâ€™s technological resurgence. formed through collaboration between tsmc, sony semiconductor solutions, and denso, the jasm plant is located in kumamoto and marks the first stage of the industrial revitalization plan. jasmâ€™s primary objective is to manufacture semiconductors locally for iot and critical embedded systems, using 22/28nm and 12/16nm process nodes. the facility targets a production capacity of 55,000 wafers per month and primarily serves japanese companies in the automotive, healthcare, telecommunications, and industrial equipment sectors. this helps reduce japanâ€™s dependency on imports and enhances its strategic resilience in the face of global disruptions. backed by public funds and a coalition of major japanese corporations, ntt, toyota, softbank, sony, denso, mitsubishi ufj, and others, jasm is designed to ensure a stable semiconductor supply for at least a decade. it is more than a production site; it is the cornerstone of a broader value chain that spans from research and materials to workforce development. jasm represents the first phase of a multi-stage plan. the second phase focuses on developing next-generation semiconductors, particularly gate-all-around technologies under 2nm. this effort is led by rapidus corporation, an industrial entity supported by the government and key national players. rapidus collaborates with international partners such as ibm, for technology transfer, and europeâ€™s imec, for collaborative research. the third phase aims to establish a global collaborative framework, integrating research in quantum, photonic, and novel computing architectures. to support these ambitions, japan has created institutions such as the leading-edge semiconductor technology center, an open research platform uniting universities, public institutes, and industry players. the goal is to build a domestic innovation hub capable of competing with centers of excellence in taiwan, south korea, and the united states. massive investments are being made in euv equipment, pilot lines, and the rapid integration of r&d outcomes into production. this strategy also includes a national talent development plan targeting the creation of two million digitally skilled professionals. the government works closely with regional authorities, universities, technical schools, and businesses to build training consortia. in kyushu, for instance, institutions such as kumamoto university and technical colleges collaborate with jasm, sony, micron, and screen to offer hands-on training, industrial site visits, and curricula aligned with real industry needs. this like many companies, $crm salesforce seems to be caught up in the latest wave of tariff and trade war headlines. however, salesforceâ€™s business is largely insulated from the impact of tariffs because it operates as a cloud-based software company rather than a producer or distributor of physical goods. salesforceâ€™s core offerings (crm, marketing automation, and ai-powered tools) are delivered digitally via the internet, which means they donâ€™t involve cross-border shipments that would be subject to import duties. as a result, the company has no direct exposure to tariffs that typically affect physical supply chains, raw materials, or components. while salesforce operates internationally, most of its services are hosted in regional cloud data centers, minimizing cross-border data flow issues that could be affected by trade tensions. yes, itâ€™s true that the company could still face some indirect effects of tariffs. if trade tensions spark broader economic slowdowns or increase uncertainty in certain industries, salesforce may experience reduced enterprise software spending or customer budget tightening. but even so, compared to hardware or manufacturing-heavy tech firms, salesforce is structurally resilient to tariffs, and its subscription-based, cloud-native model makes it one of the more insulated tech companies in times of rising trade protectionism.

breaking: japan examines whether to review ev charging standard the japanese government will closely examine whether it is necessary to review the charging standard for electric vehicles, as the united states regards it as a non-tariff trade barrier. in an nhk program on sunday, japanese prime minister ishiba shigeru referred to ongoing bilateral negotiations on us tariffs on japanese imports. ishiba said he believes that cutting the trade deficit is top priority for the administration of president donald trump. the united states has demanded an increase in the number of us-made vehicles that japan imports. last month, the office of the united states trade representative criticized japan in a report. it said the country is impeding access to its automotive market through a variety of non-tariff barriers. the report cited differences in vehicle safety regulations and the japanese government's handling of charging standards for electric vehicles, called chademo. the japanese government is examining measures for the next round of negotiations, and closely looking into whether it is necessary review ev charging standards. the government would not make easy concessions due to the impact on auto industries, as it is key for japan. the japan automobile importers association says 227,202 cars made by foreign-brand vehicles were imported and sold in japan last year. that's about five percent of the new cars sold in the country in 2024. most were german brand cars. us brand cars didn't account for any high percentage points. mercedes-benz sold 53,195 vehicles, bmw followed with 35,240, and volkswagen was 22,779. sales of american cars in japan in 2024 were about 16,700 units. us brand jeep, which is under the umbrella of european automaker stellantis, sold 9,633 units in japan last year, while auto giant general motors' chevrolet sold 587 units, and cadillac was at 449 units. tesla does not release the number of cars sold in japan, but the us ev giant was likely to have sold more than 5,600 cars based on statistics in the country. some japanese dealers point out that the features of american cars, including their sizes and fuel efficiency, don't meet the needs of the japanese market in the first place.

interesting way to estimate the value of international trade involving â€œpureâ€data. â€œâ€¦we looked at how much alphabet pays corporations such as apple to set google search as a default on ios devices, which alphabet treats as a tac (traffic acquisition cost). over time, these payments to apple alone have risen from us$1 billion in 2014 to us$18 billion in 2021. if we divide this amount by the number of active iphones, we can get close to the value of this data for alphabet. in 2014, the resulting number was $2.26 per person, and in 2021, it was $14.62. these numbers donâ€™t seem particularly high, but they need to be adjusted by the average tac rate that alphabet pays, to calculate how valuable this data is for alphabet. the tac rate in 2021 was 22 percent, representing what alphabet was willing to pay for the data â€” meaning that this dataâ€™s value for alphabet was actually more like $66.46 in 2021 per person, and its total value was $81.26 per person (that is, $14.62 + $66.46). if we then extrapolate to the population of canada (41.6 million), the total value of canadaâ€™s data extracted by alphabet was around $3.4 billion in 2021. that means alphabet alone is extracting us$3.4 billionsâ€™ worth of data from canadians every year, a pretty hefty amount that is missing from trade statistics.â€

the trump administration plans to rescind biden-era ai chip curbs as part of a broader effort to revise semiconductor trade restrictions that have drawn strong opposition from major tech companies and foreign governments. the repeal, which is not yet final, seeks to refashion a policy launched under president joe biden that created three broad tiers of countries for regulating the export of chips from nvidia corp. and others. the trump administration will not enforce the so-called ai diffusion rule when it takes effect on may 15. the changes are taking shape as president donald trump prepares for a trip to the middle east, where a number of countries including saudi arabia and the united arab emirates have bristled at restrictions on their ability to acquire ai chips. the governmentâ€™s decision could be announced as soon as thursday. unveiled during bidenâ€™s last week in office, the diffusion rule established new us licensing obligations for ai chip shipments to much of the world, as a final salvo after years of escalating restrictions on semiconductor trade. the measure sought to prevent china from acquiring ai chip technology via intermediaries and to bring more nations into the us orbit by setting security requirements to access best-in-class american technology. â€œthe biden ai rule is overly complex, overly bureaucratic, and would stymie american innovation,â€ the commerce departmentâ€™s bureau of industry and security said in a statement released by a spokesperson. â€œwe will be replacing it with a much simpler rule that unleashes american innovation and ensures american ai dominance.â€ via

groundbreaking? titan is armyâ€™s first ai-defined vehicle and stands for tactical intelligence targeting access node, mobile ground station developed by palantir technologies for the u.s. army. it integrates data from space, air, and terrestrial sensors to provide real-time, actionable intelligence for enhanced mission command and long-range precision strikes. the system uses artificial intelligence and machine learning to process vast amounts of data, reducing the time between data collection and precision targeting. palantir, as the prime contractor, leads a team including northrop grumman, anduril industries, and l3harris technologies to deliver 10 prototypes under a $178.4 million contract awarded in march 2024. these prototypes include five advanced variants, integrated with tactical trucks like the m1083, and five basic variants, mounted on joint light tactical vehicles. titan supports the armyâ€™s multi-domain operations and joint all domain command and control (jadc2) by fusing sensor data to improve battlefield decision-making. company expects to complete all 10 systems by 2026, after which the army will decide whether to carry titan into full-rate production. although the service hasnâ€™t said how many systems it will buy, officials have estimated between 100 and 150 units. titan offers a flexible and scalable ground station designed to modernize the army with the latest deep sensing and sensor fusion capabilities. key capabilities: -reducing sensor-to-shooter timelines -integrated with army and joint fires systems -reducing soldier workflow burdens and cognitive load -deeper sensing that can interoperate with modern sensors -accurate and effective targeting enabled by ai/ml -enabling collection and processing while on the move the u.s. army now has in hand a few tactical intelligence targeting access nodes, state-of-the-art trucks that promise to streamline the battlefield process of spotting, tracking and blasting. why it matters: the program â€” years in the making, but also on time and budget â€” is critical to the defense department's connect-everything-everywhere dream of combined joint all-domain command and control. it also "or potentially, depending on what you think the merits of it are: 'made in the united states' maybe at their texas facility or something else but with a longer term plan of maybe five or ten years frankly, of being able to actually manufacture the phones here," he went on. "if he were to come to you with something like that, do you think that then there would be a reprieve for the next couple years as they get their house in order?" asked ross sorkin. in this moment of economic transformation, driven by shifting trade relationships and the rise of new technologies such as ai, the federal government and the private sector need to work together. the government should seek out expertise from canadaâ€™s companies, and companies need to provide support, including seconding employees for short-term government placements. canada has a history of just this kind of collaboration. during the second world war, c.d. howe helped organize over a hundred of canada's top industrial leaders to work for the government to organize and bolster the war efforts, producing everything from ammunition to airplanes, and not only helping to secure canada's victory in the war but transforming the country into a modern industrial nation. these leaders were called the "dollar-a-year men" because they devoted their time and energy to serving the country for a nominal salary of a dollar a year plus expenses, though many declined even to charge for their expenses. after the war, senior professionals from the private sector continued to support the growing canadian public sector. in 1971, the government developed the interchange canada program to allow top members of industry to work with government agencies for a short period to provide their know-how and management expertise to help keep costs low and ensure effective services. today, canada faces serious challenges in ai adoption, defense capabilities, enterprise software, strategic procurement, and moreâ€”areas where there are skilled experts in private sector companies. we need their technical knowledge now. by having private sector experts help the government directly it will empower our public sector leaders to develop policies that are more relevant in our fast-changing world helping our economy grow faster, our public service use cutting-edge tools, and our military have the best equipment. like the dollar-a-year men who served during wartime, canada needs today's leaders to step up and contribute directly. governments should welcome additional expertise from the private sector and set up systems to use it effectively. and, companies should loan some of their best technical talent to the government while covering their salaries. by enhancing the existing interchange canada program and creating fast-track approval processes to remove bureaucratic barriers that typically slow private sector integration we can embed private sector experts in key public sector roles and leverage their skills to unlock new levels of productivity and growth. you can read the hi everyone! this chart shows 12-month forward p/e ratios comparing today's ai bubble to the infamous dot-com era. the top 10 stocks now trade at nearly 30x forward earnings, matching the 2000 peak that preceded the tech crash. what i'm seeing in the economics: unlike 2000 when many companies had no earnings, today's ai leaders are genuinely profitable. but here's what worries me: companies like openai expect $12 billion in revenue while running $5 billion annual losses. they're openly undercharging customers because investors are subsidizing the true costs. the circular money flow i'm tracking: i've been watching the magnificent seven spend $500 billion to generate $15 billion in ai revenue, much of it circular. microsoft invests in openai, openai pays microsoft for azure, microsoft buys nvidia chips. it's financial musical chairs within the same ecosystem. why i focus on forward p/e ratios: these 28-30x forward valuations assume companies will maintain hypergrowth for years. but when ai subsidies end and true costs emerge, businesses that replaced workers thinking ai would stay cheap face a harsh reset. i've seen estimates that some ai queries consume as much electricity as running a microwave for 24 hours. the risk i'm most concerned about: unlike 2000, today's bubble is concentrated in fewer, larger companies with massive index weightings. when these megacaps stumble, the entire market gets dragged down disproportionately. what history teaches me: revolutionary technology and unsustainable economics can coexist. the internet was transformative in 1999, but that didn't prevent a massive crash. even profitable companies like microsoft took 15 years to reach new highs after the bubble burst. the question i keep asking isn't whether ai is real, but whether current prices reflect the economics of actually running these systems profitably. hedgie

shocking: trump's ai action plan restricts the enforcement power of the federal trade commission (ftc) against ai companies, and the ftc has already begun deleting articles criticizing abusive ai practices: under the section "remove red tape and onerous regulation," one of the white house's recommended policy actions is to: - "review all ftc investigations commenced under the previous administration to ensure that they do not advance theories of liability that unduly burden ai innovation. furthermore, review all ftc final orders, consent decrees,and injunctions, and, where appropriate, seek to modify or set aside any that unduly burden ai innovation." it seems that this policy has already started being implemented. why? i often recommend to my students various interesting ftc articles that help us understand what the u.s. interprets as abusive, unfair, or prohibited ai practices and how enforcement in the u.s. might look like. in the past few months, however, i noticed that many of these ftc articles have been deleted, including popular ones such as: - keep your ai claims in check - the luring test: ai and the engineering of consumer trust - watching the detectives: suspicious marketing claims for tools that spot ai generated content - canâ€™t lose what you never had: claims about digital ownership and creation in the age of generative ai the ftc has been extremely important in keeping tech companies in check in the past few years, and many (including me) had hopes that it would be essential in tackling unfair and abusive ai practices. trump, however, has ordered a broad review of the ftc's actions with the goal of "removing red tape." why do i say broad? - what is an investigation that "advances theories of liability that unduly burdens ai innovation"? - what is covered under "theory of liability"? - how will the ai innovation burden be assessed? this policy is so broadly framed that it can mean anything the white house wants. it's unclear to me how effective ai-related ftc enforcement will be in the upcoming years, or if it will have any power to enforce anything against ai companies. i'll keep you posted. - never miss my analyses and curations on ai: join my newsletter's 70,300+ subscribers (link below).

backward. production plummeted by nearly 60% qoq due to tariff-related supply chain disruptions, completely erasing the last two quarters of gross profit progress. this single-quarter event highlights the extreme fragility of their manufacturing profitability to volume fluctuations and external shocks. as a direct result, management has worsened the full-year adjusted ebitda loss guidance. the software & jv business: in sharp contrast, the partnership with volkswagen has begun bearing fruit immediately and impressively. rivian recognized $182 million in high-margin software and development revenue from the jv this quarter, providing a powerful new financial cushion. this, combined with the successful launch of the well-reviewed gen 2 quad-motor r1 and progress on the autonomy front (e.g., google maps partnership), strengthens the long-term technology-as-a-differentiator thesis. conclusion: the marketâ€™s reaction will likely be torn. the severe miss on gross profit is a major negative, questioning the near-term viability of the r1 platformâ€™s profitability. however, the unexpected and immediate contribution from the vw jv, coupled with strong liquidity ($7.5b in cash) and positive operating cash flow for the quarter, provides a powerful counter-narrative. the story is shifting from a pure-play ev manufacturer to a company whose path to profitability may be paved more by high-margin software/jv revenue than by vehicle sales in the medium term. 4. themes, drivers, and concerns themes & drivers: how they evolved navigating severe macro & tariff headwinds (materialized & intensified): last quarterâ€™s primary concern became this quarterâ€™s painful reality. the â€œcouple thousand dollarsâ€ of cost impact has now manifested as a full-blown production bottleneck, halting nearly 60% of their output and derailing profitability. this remains the number one risk. volkswagen jv (evolved from driver to key contributor): this has accelerated from a future capital source to a present, high-margin revenue stream. the jv contributed $182m in revenue and helped drive the software & services segment to a 34% gross margin. this is now a critical pillar of rivianâ€™s financial model, providing a much-needed offset to the volatile automotive business. in-house technology as a strategic moat (strengthened): this theme gained momentum. the gen 2 r1 quad-motor launch provides a tangible product proof point for their in-house capabilities. the new google maps partnership and the plan to open a london ai office show continued investment and external validation. r2 platform as the transformative growth engine (maintained): the narrative remains unchanged. r2 is the future. progress is steady (normal facility expansion is complete), and management added a key new target: r2 cost of revenues per unit is estimated to be â€œless than halfâ€ that of r1. cost reduction & margin improvement (driver derailed): this driver went off the rails in q2. the focus on operational efficiency was completely overshadowed by the massive negative impact of low volume on fixed cost absorption. the path to the â€œmodest positive gross profitâ€ for fy2025 now looks nearly impossible. concerns: how they evolved reversal to negative gross profit (new & critical concern): the swing from +$206m to -$206m in gross profit is alarming. it demonstrates that r1 profitability is a knifeâ€™s edge, highly susceptible to volume. this raises serious questions about the standalone economic viability of the r1 platform ahead of the r2 launch. significant tariff and trade policy impact (confirmed concern): this is no longer a risk; itâ€™s a realized issue that directly impacted q2 results and is the stated cause for the worsened ebitda guide. weakening suggests demand is holding up, at least enough to meet their constrained production. inventory build (resolved concern): the overproduction in q1 was successfully drawn down in q2, as deliveries significantly outpaced production. this is no longer an immediate concern. 5. key questions for the earnings call on gross profit volatility: you reversed from +$206m to -$206m in gross profit, ai and machine learning are poised to fundamentally transform retail trading, shifting the focus from passive alert services to a dynamic, educational, and empowering experience. and the team at the trading syndicate and beyond the trades will be leading the charge shortly. for the serious few the problem with alert services alert services, while popular, have a significant flaw: they treat trading as a "follow the leader" activity. they provide signalsâ€”"buy this," "sell that"â€”without providing any context or education. this approach creates a dependency on the service and prevents a trader from developing the critical thinking skills necessary for long-term success. it's like giving someone a fish instead of teaching them how to fish. when the alerts stop or the market changes, the trader is left without the underlying knowledge to adapt. this can lead to frustration and financial loss, as the trader is essentially gambling on someone else's analysis without understanding the rationale. the rise of the ai-powered educator from the trading syndicate the future of retail trading education will be centered on personalized, data-driven learning. ai and machine learning will act as a personal mentor, helping traders understand the "why" behind market movements. this is a profound shift from a model of dependency to one of self-sufficiency. 1. real-time, adaptive backtesting traditional backtesting is a static process. a trader tests a strategy against historical data and gets a single result. itâ€™s a snapshot in time. ai, however, can provide a dynamic, adaptive backtesting environment. it can simulate various market conditionsâ€”bull, bear, volatile, or trendingâ€”and show a trader how their strategy would have performed. more importantly, it can analyze the strategy's weaknesses and suggest specific improvements, such as where to place a tighter stop-loss or when to be more patient with a position. this allows for a deeper understanding of a strategy's strengths and weaknesses without risking real capital. 2. pattern recognition beyond the human eye the sheer volume of market data is overwhelming for a human. ai and machine learning can process millions of data points, including price data, volume, and even alternative data like social media sentiment and news headlines, in milliseconds. it can then identify subtle, non-obvious patterns and correlations that a human trader would likely miss. instead of simply generating an alert, an ai system can highlight these patterns and explain why they are significant. this teaches the trader to look for these unique market signatures on their own, enhancing their analytical skills and market intuition. 3. behavioral and psychological coaching emotional bias is one of the biggest challenges for retail traders. fear, greed, and fomo (fear of missing out) can lead to impulsive, irrational decisions. ai can act as a psychological co-pilot, monitoring a trader's behavior and providing real-time feedback. for example, if a trader is taking on too much risk or over-trading, the ai can flag the behavior and explain the statistical probability of success based on their past performance. it can help the trader stick to their predefined trading plan and remove emotion from the equation, a crucial step in becoming a consistently profitable trader. 4. the creation of a personal trading "dna" ai can analyze a trader's past performance to create a comprehensive profile of their trading "dna." it can identify their risk tolerance, their most profitable setups, the times of day they perform best, and even the market conditions that are most favorable for their style. this data-driven self-awareness is the ultimate educational tool. it allows traders to double down on what works and avoid their personal pitfalls, leading to a highly customized and effective trading approach. in essence, ai and machine learning are not just a tool for automation; they are the future of financial education. by shifting the focus from generating alerts to fostering genuine understanding, these technologies will empower a new generation of retail traders to navigate the markets with intelligence, discipline, and a deep, data-backed understanding of their own strategies. this is an evolution from being told what to do to truly learning how to think like a professional.

china is withholding its 2025 rare earth quotas, creating uncertainty across evs, defense, and electronics. the opacity suggests quota data is now a bargaining chip in us-china trade talks. china usually posts annual caps on mining and on refining, called separation, so producers worldwide can plan. this year the first batch reportedly went to china rare earth group and china northern rare earth, but the tonnages are undisclosed, which is a sharp break from routine. quotas matter because they cap raw ore output and processed oxides, which feed magnets used in motors, wind turbines, radars, and guidance systems. when the signal disappears, buyers guess demand, prices swing, and downstream production schedules slip. western buyers have been adding inventory after slower shipments, while beijing has warned firms against stockpiling, a posture that preserves maximum leverage on timing and price. recent history shows the baseline. in 2024, mining quotas totaled 270,000 tonnes, up 6% from 2023, after a 21% jump the year before. separation quotas reached 254,000 tonnes, up 4%, also far below the prior 21% increase. pair that slowdown with tighter export enforcement, plus arrests over smuggling, and the picture is clear, china is protecting control of the supply chain. the practical impact is immediate. auto, wind, and defense planners in the us, europe, and japan lose visibility on feedstock, lead times lengthen, and non-china projects face financing questions without a clear view of chinese output. if quota data stays hidden, expect more precautionary buying, more price volatility, and more pressure to localize separation capacity outside china. - scmp. com/economy/china-economy/article/3322245/china-hiding-its-rare-earth-production-plans-us-tensions-fuel-speculation

under president donaldtrumpâ€™s administration, multiple countries struck tariff deals with the u.s. to secure market access amid escalating trade tensions. trump aimed to reposition america as the central hub of global trade by imposing tariffs and renegotiating agreements to favor u.s. economic interests. however, these efforts have not unfolded as planned, leading to significant shifts in global trade dynamics. key developments and challenges include: - many countries that agreed to tariff deals with trump are actively pursuing alternative trade partnerships and supply chains to reduce their dependence on the u.s. market and to hedge against the unpredictability of u.s. trade policies. - nations are diversifying their trade relations by strengthening ties within regional blocs such as asean, the europeanunion, and agreements like the comprehensive and progressive agreement for trans-pacific partnership (cptpp), which exclude the u.s. - trump's trade policies, characterized by tariff impositions on chinese goods and others, sparked retaliatory tariffs and trade disputes, disrupting global supply chains and increasing costs for companies worldwide. this pushed many global players to reassess their dependence on the u.s. market. - the vision of making america the cornerstone of international trade has faced resistance both from global partners and domestic political challenges, weakening the u.s.'s leadership role in shaping global economic rules. - as a result, the global trade ecosystem is becoming more multipolar, with economic influence and market access spreading beyond the u.s. to include china, the eu, and emerging economic clusters. this contrasts with trumpâ€™s aspirations for americaâ€™s centrality in world trade. in summary, despite tariff deals aimed at securing u.s. market dominance, countries are developing alternative trade strategies and partnerships, underscoring that things are not going according to trumpâ€™s original trade vision.

as of late august 2025, former president donald trump has made strong statements regarding digital taxes and regulations imposed by other countries, which could have significant implications for american tech companies. specifically, threats of tariffs and export restrictions. trump has threatened to impose "substantial" tariffs on imports from, and restrict the export of technology and computer chips to, countries that impose digital services taxes or implement digital regulations he deems discriminatory towards american tech companies. targeted regulations and taxes: these threats are primarily aimed at the european union's digital markets act (dma) and digital services act (dsa), as well as digital services taxes in countries like the uk, france, italy, and spain. x has repeatedly challenged and not complied with uk requests for data, primarily under the new online safety act (osa), which came into full effect in july 2025. x, has faced significant pressure from the uk, and the uk government defends its online safety act. the uk regulators under the authority of the online safety act, threat x with the potential fines for non-compliance. the u.s. department of justice (doj) is concerned about foreign government access to u.s. sensitive personal data, leading to a new rule restricting such data transfers to "countries of concern". concurrently, the u.s. administration has voiced concerns that the eu's digital services act (dsa) imposes "overly broad controls" and risks undermining freedom of expression by expanding definitions of illegal content, potentially disadvantaging american tech companies. doj rule on data access: the doj's final rule (effective april 8, 2025) aims to prevent "countries of concern," such as china, iran, russia, and north korea, from accessing u.s. sensitive personal data. the rule prohibits and restricts "bulk" data transactions involving certain types of sensitive data, including human genomic, biometric, precise geolocation, and personal financial data. application: the rule applies to vendor agreements and employment agreements that involve these restricted data transfers from . u.s. doj concerns content moderation: u.s. officials and tech companies argue that the dsa's definitions of "illegal content" are too broad and could lead to censorship, particularly affecting political and religious speech. there are concerns that the dsa's content moderation requirements and potential fines for non-compliance could curb freedom of expression. this non-compliance has included refusing to provide data and condemning the osa as a threat to free speech. government data requests uk data requests: in the second half of 2024, x refused the uk government's requests for data. x did not provide data. challenge to the online safety act x has been a vocal critic of the osa, citing concerns that the legislation is a "suppression of the people" and compromises free speech. the u.s. department of justice may have an official investigation against the uk's online safety act (osa), there is no u.s. federal legislation by that name: digital markets act (dma) and digital services act (dsa). a u.s. state department report in 2025 criticized the uk's osa for potentially "chilling free speech". the department of justice (doj) and federal bureau of investigation (fbi) may have a direct u.s. legislative action against the uk's online safety act (osa). the u.s. state department has expressed concerns about the osa's potential impact on free speech, according to 2025 reports. following the osa's enforcement in july 2025, x published a statement calling for "significant adjustments" to the law. the company criticized regulators for taking a "heavy-handed approach" and creating unnecessary bureaucracy. the u.s. state department's 2024 report on human rights expressed concerns that the osa could lead to serious restrictions on freedom of expression in the uk.

radio-frequency integrated circuits (rfic) (aka "radio on a chip") and software-defined radio (sdr) devices are major safety and security threats and likely the real reason behind technology tariffs and outright sales bans. amazon, ebay, temu, alibaba, and many other sites have made a habit of selling highly compromised devices for pennies on the dollar. there are strong connections (often outright ownership) between manufacturers of these devices and nations with vested interests in disrupting or otherwise disabling u.s. infrastructure nationwide. cheap electronics can come with a much higher real price. amazon-sourced solar lights that we purchased to light dark areas of our farm have strange, inefficient, and over-wrought chip configurations and battery packs stuffed with circuits that frankly don't make sense and have therefore been disposed of. ditto for cheap usb lights and fans. think carefully before purchasing deals "too good to be true"; that amazon instant savings deal or intro temu deal may indeed cost more than it is worth.

the intersection of trade, debt, demographics, ai and politics appear different in each part of the world. therefore, the challenges and opportunities in europe, china, the us and india are unique. a flagging hegemon attempts to stave off decline, a near peer seeks to establish itself as the dominant power and rising nations try to become great powers. to achieve this, existing tools are used, new tools, developed, and fresh regulations, imposed. due to fiscal indiscipline and aging demographics, debt has piled up. the enormous strain this imposes can be addressed through: inflating away debt by debasing the dollar, investing in disruptive technologies, coercing countries to invest in the us, issuing stablecoins, mainstreaming cryptocurrencies, collecting visa fees and imposing tariffs. for over four decades, importing low cost goods from china enabled western interest rates to broadly follow a downward trajectory. new industries financed long runway r&d projects and cash-burning ventures. a vast share of us gdp growth was generated by technology firms that benefited from low rates. many firms relied on skilled labor not just to keep costs down but also harness talent unavailable at home. the us hopes that the technology catalyzes growth and reduces goods and services inflation before sovereign debt risks reach a tipping point. as ai develops at an exponential rate, a services-heavy us is set to lose jobs. the unemployment rate for graduates in their mid-20s is ~6% and growing. this is sharply higher than the national average of 4.2%.phasing out foreign workers in a period of what is effectively austerity for the middle class is viewed as politically expedient in the short term and economically viable in the long term. today, dependence on china and india is viewed with suspicion and worry. the dollar is far too strong to onshore a significant amount of manufacturing, which china enjoys economies of scale in. services on the other hand, will fast get automated. foreign workers cannot be perceived as beneficiaries in a labor market faced with growing constraints. offshoring services will continue but aiâ€™s contagion effect will eventually spread, reducing labor arbitrage. as robots get deployed in manufacturing, the marginal cost of production will decline globally. the labor arbitrage with china will eventually reduce. as ai and robotics mature, they will accelerate deglobalization. with that, the nature of international trade and the reserve currency will also change. on the surface, trump is appealing to a radical base. he earns political points from millions who are ill equipped to replace lost migrant workers. 57% of americans read at a level below 8th grade. 62% are unable to solve math problems needing over three steps. education standards have consistently declined in recent years. turning a country built on immigration into a closed society simply results in a talent shortage over the medium term. the appeal of the us as a land of opportunity has been dented for the foreseeable future. meanwhile, attempts to stymie the rise of the worldâ€™s fastest growing large economy, will likely fail. favorable demographics and a penchant for performing under pressure enable india to adapt, gain productivity and reduce foreign dependencies. the muscle memory from this can build the foundation for sustainable yet explosive growth. the trade in which remittances more than netted off brain drain is expiring at an opportune time. going forward, technological competitiveness and capability will contribute more to cnp and leverage in international affairs. india can capitalize on the disruption in developed economies. reshoring talent can drive growth, but internal constraints remain. bureaucratic red tape, political apathy and weak urban infrastructure limit talent absorption. inadequate capital allocation towards sovereign ai and frontier technologies means that a forward looking r&d ecosystem remains underdeveloped.

bloomberg is out with an article today about how $ter $klac $lrcx have morphed into the new leaders of the ai chip trade. the article tries to attribute the outperformance to traders just trying to find more obscure winners in the ai capex spending boom. but it is more nuanced than this. what do these stocks have in common? they're all deeply levered to the physical ai boom. klac - physical ai requires massive chip reliability. a humanoid robot or self-driving car cannot afford a chip defect that bricks its control system in the field. klac tools ensure yields are high and defects are minimal in the advanced logic and memory chips that power edge ai devices and robotics. lrcx - many physical ai devices will require specialized form factors (low power, ruggedized, 3d nand, advanced packaging, etc). lrcx's etch/deposition tech is essential for scaling transistor density and enabling 3d architectures used in energy-efficient ai chips. ter - they've got a whole robotics arm and are literally building collaborative robots (cobots) point being: the ai capex spending wave is continuing with vigor, but within that spending wave, the spend is shifting towards physical ai plays. that's why stocks like ter, klac, & lrcx have been outrunning the competition. that will likely remain true as we push into 2026.
